Go Generics are parameters which can be used to create functions which can accept any type of input. For example: 

func printHello(hello interface{}) {
	fmt.Println(hello)
}

// Usage

type User struct {
	Name string
	Age int
}

var user User
printHello(user) // Prints: "User{Name: "Bob", Age: 30}

Generics are a feature in programming languages that allow a function or method to operate on data of different types. An interface is a type in Go which defines a set of methods that a struct must implement. Go generics allow you to define a type which the function or method can act upon, and this type does not have to be an interface. For example:

// Generic function which takes a type T
func printHello<T>(hello T) {
	fmt.Println(hello)
}

// Usage

printHello(30) // Prints: 30
printHello(User{}) // Prints: User{Name: "Bob", Age: 30}
